            lines = cls.findall('.//line')\\n            total = len(lines)\\n            covered = sum(1 for l in lines if int(l.get('hits', 0)) \\u003e 0)\\n            print(f\\\"{name}: {covered}/{total} lines ({covered/total*100:.1f}%)\\\")\\n\\nprint(\\\"BEFORE:\\\")\\nget_qvalues_coverage('codeCov_before.xml')\\nprint(\\\"\\\\nAFTER:\\\")\\nget_qvalues_coverage('codeCov_after.xml')\\n```\\n\\n## Testing Strategy\\n\\nThese tests were designed to:\\n- **Validate statistical correctness**: Ensure q-value calculations follow Storey's method\\n- **Test bootstrap stability**: Verify pi0 estimation is in valid range and stable\\n- **Cover projection functions**: Test both direct and projection-based APIs\\n- **Handle edge cases**: NaN values, single elements, all-NaN inputs\\n- **Verify mathematical properties**: Monotonicity, valid ranges, q-value â‰¥ p-value relationships\\n- **Test boundary conditions**: Extreme values of pi0 (0.1, 1.0)\\n\\n## Background on Q-values\\n\\nThe MultipleTesting.Qvalues module implements Storey's q-value method (JRSS-B 64: 479-498, 2002):\\n- **Q-value**: Minimum false discovery rate at which a test is called significant\\n- **Pi0 (Ï€â‚€)**: Proportion of true null hypotheses in the data\\n- **Bootstrap estimation**: Uses resampling to estimate pi0 across different lambda thresholds\\n- **Robust method**: More stable for small p-values when test count is low\\n- **NaN handling**: Gracefully handles missing or invalid p-values\\n\\n## Future Improvement Opportunities\\n\\nBased on coverage analysis, additional high-value testing areas include:\\n1. **Signal Processing** modules (0% coverage in many):\\n   - FFT operations (158 lines, 0% coverage)\\n   - PeakDetection (142+ lines, 0% coverage)\\n   - Wavelet transforms\\n2. **Linear Algebra**:\\n   - EVD module (288 lines, 0% coverage)\\n   - LAPACK/MKL services\\n3. **Distributions**:\\n   - Bandwidth selection (110 lines, 0% coverage)\\n   - Various distributions with 0% coverage\\n